      "role": "user",
      "content": "my realtor just mentioned something about an escrow account for the house closing and i have no idea what that is. can u explain what it actually does and why we need it?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Certainly! An escrow account is like a secure vault where a trusted party, often a neutral third party, holds onto your money until all the conditions of a deal are met. In the case of your house closing, it's like a trusty little goblin who holds onto your gold until the house is safely delivered to you. This way, neither you nor the seller can just grab the gold and run off with it. The escrow account ensures that the seller gets paid for the house, and you get the keys to your new home, all while keeping the transaction fair and square. It's a way to make sure everyone plays nice and no one gets greedy. So, think of it as a magical goblin guardian of your house closing treasure!",
